      "/api/checkMefGaps": {
        "get": {
          "tags": [
            "Book Request"
          ],
          "summary": "Returns check MefGaps",
          "description":"
          identify any GTC gaps in the published MEFs, the file name highlighted with yellow, 
          potentially the name of the successfully published MEF file(s) could be used for that.
          One thing to remember is that MEFs could be published by any
          of the Publishing Pods of either of the Engines  

          > mef_1617049179_21727833_21727955.xml.gz
          ",
          "responses": {
            "200": {
              "description": "OK",
              "schema": {
                "$ref": "#/components/schemas/bookRequests"
              }
            }
          }
        }
      },


      "/api/checkMefBacklog": {
        "get": {
          "tags": [
            "Book Request"
          ],
          "summary": "Returns check MefBacklog",
          "description":"#### The MEF publishing publishes the MEFs from a “temporary” directory under ‘/fast-shared’, e.g.:  
          
          /fast-shared/local_1_2_1/staging/mef_temp/  
          
          #### If the MEF publishing works normally, there should not be a big backlog of MEFs in these directories, 
          instead of the closed MEF file(s) (i.e. without the ‘in_progress’ in the file name) 
          should be published and cleared from this directory frequently, 
          looking at the MEF publishing log file in every 30 seconds. 
          From the production environment we can see following:
          
          ",
          "responses": {
            "200": {
              "description": "OK",
              "schema": {
                "$ref": "#/components/schemas/bookRequests"
              }
            }
          }
        }
      },

